Preheat your #oven{} to 220°C. Halve, peel and thinly slice the @red onion{1}(halved, peeled and thinly sliced). Peel and grate the @garlic clove{1}(peeled and grated) (or use a #garlic press{}). Cut the @aubergine{1} in half lengthways. Score diagonal criss-crosses into the flesh, 1cm apart. Go deep but avoid piercing the skin. Drizzle some @oil{} on each half and season with @salt{} and @pepper{}. Place on a lined #baking tray{} and pop on the top shelf of your oven. Cook until soft and browned, ~{25-30%minutes}.

Heat a drizzle of @oil{} in a large #saucepan{} on medium heat. Add the garlic and @chermoula spice mix{1} and cook for ~{1%minute}. Tip in the @freekeh{100%g}, then pour in the @water{200%ml}. Stir in the @vegetable stock powder{1/2}, and bring to a simmer. Turn the heat down to low and put a #lid{} on. Cook the freekeh for ~{15%minutes}, then remove from the heat. Leave to the side for ~{5%minutes} (still covered) or until everything else is ready.

While the freekeh cooks, heat a splash of @oil{} in another large saucepan on medium heat and add the onion. Cook until really soft, stirring every few mins, ~{8-10%minutes}. Next, add the @balsamic vinegar{12%ml}. Turn the heat to low, put the lid on and cook for ~{3-4%minutes}. Remove the pan from the heat. While everything cooks, chop the @cucumber{1/2} into small chunks. Pick the @mint{1/2} leaves from their stalks and roughly chop (discard the stalks).

When the aubergine is soft all the way through, remove it from your oven and preheat your #grill{} to high. Squash down the flesh of each aubergine half with a #fork{} (see picture). Crumble in the @goat's cheese{125%g}, grind over some @pepper{} and place under your grill until the cheese is brown and bubbling, ~{5-6%minutes}.

Meanwhile, zest the @lemon{1/2} and cut in half. Squeeze the lemon juice into a #mixing bowl{} with the @olive oil{2%tbsp}, a pinch of @salt{} and @pepper{} and the @wholegrain mustard{1/2}. Whisk with a fork. Add in the cucumber chunks and three-quarters of the mint. Toss together.

Stir the lemon zest into the freekeh, taste and add salt and pepper if you feel it needs it. Serve the aubergine on a bed of freekeh with the cucumber and mint salad on the side. Spoon over the caramelised onion and finish with a sprinkling of the remaining mint. Enjoy!

> Freekeh, made from durum wheat, makes a great replacement for rice in this deliciously simple vegetarian recipe. Once cooked, freekeh has a natural al dente bite and nutty texture which works brilliantly with silky aubergine, crunchy cucumber and creamy grilled goat's cheese. Packed with veggie goodness and fresh, delicious flavours, we've got a feeling that this is about to become your new go-to recipe!